      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/software-qa",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA: Version-controlled solver with documented test suite",
        "description": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1) must be under version control with a documented regression test suite covering blood-analogue laminar and turbulent pipe-flow benchmarks. All simulation scripts committed to institutional repository with audit trail."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 is an FDA-recognized solver covered by vendor SQA documentation and an internal regression suite. Simulation scripts are version-controlled in the FDA OSEL GitLab instance. SQA level 2 is required and achieved for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification: Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for Navier-Stokes",
        "description": "Solver must demonstrate second-order spatial convergence on a manufactured solution for incompressible Navier-Stokes with a non-Newtonian viscosity model. Observed order of accuracy must be within 10% of theoretical order."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has published MMS verification results for incompressible viscous flow. Internal verification tests confirmed second-order spatial convergence (observed OOA = 1.93) on a Carreau-viscosity manufactured solution representative of blood rheology. Required and achieved level are both 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/discretization-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "GCI < 5% on hemolysis index QoI across three systematically refined meshes",
        "description": "Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Celik et al. (2008) on three systematically refined meshes (refinement ratio r = 1.3). GCI on the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) must be less than 5% at all five operating points."
      },
      "rationale": "Three meshes were generated with systematic refinement (coarse 2.1 M, medium 3.7 M, fine 6.4 M cells). GCI on NIH ranged from 1.8% to 4.2% across operating points, satisfying the <5% criterion. Apparent order of convergence was 1.87, consistent with second-order scheme."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Experimental boundary conditions replicated within ±5% of nominal flow and pressure",
        "description": "CFD inlet flow rates and outlet pressures must match the FDA GCBP experimental conditions within ±5%. Blood-analogue fluid properties (glycerol-water, viscosity 0.00345 Pa·s at 37°C) must be applied consistently."
      },
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions were set to match published FDA GCBP experimental conditions (Hariharan et al. 2011). Inlet flow rates of 2.5, 3.5, 5.0, 6.5, and 7.0 L/min were replicated to within 1%. Fluid properties used glycerol-water analogue matching experimental viscosity within 2%."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "CFD NIH within experimental uncertainty band at ≥4 of 5 operating points",
        "description": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) must fall within the experimental uncertainty band (mean ± 2 SD from FDA round-robin data) at a minimum of 4 out of 5 operating points. Relative hemolysis index RH < 1 at worst-case condition."
      },
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH agreed with experimental values within the FDA round-robin uncertainty band at all 5 operating points. RH = 0.87 at the worst-case operating point (7.0 L/min, 2000 RPM), satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. Output comparison level 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI (NIH and RH index) are directly linked to the clinical hemolysis endpoint",
        "description": "The quantities of interest extracted from the CFD model (volume-averaged scalar stress, NIH computed via Giersiepen power-law model, and RH relative to predicate) must be traceable to the clinical endpoint of device-induced hemolysis as defined in ASTM F1841."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH and RH are established hemolysis metrics per ASTM F1841 and ISO 10993-4. The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model is the industry-standard approach for CFD-based hemolysis prediction in rotary blood pumps. QoI relevance is well-documented in the literature and directly maps to the clinical decision criterion."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation experiments conducted on the same device geometry under CPB-representative conditions",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry (or a certified replica) operated within the CPB flow-speed envelope (2–8 L/min, 1500–3000 RPM). At least 3 independent experimental datasets must be used."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation was performed against FDA GCBP experimental data from the FDA round-robin study (Hariharan et al. 2011) and two independent laboratory datasets (Malinauskas et al. 2017; Craven et al. 2019), all using the certified FDA GCBP geometry under CPB-representative conditions. Validation activity relevance level 2 is achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor addresses iterative convergence errors arising from solver-specific algebraic linearisation choices that are separable from discretization error. At MRL 2 for this COU, the ASME V&V 40 credibility matrix does not require independent assessment of solver error beyond what is captured in the discretization error factor (assessed separately). Furthermore, ANSYS Fluent's pressure-based coupled solver is documented to reach residuals below 1×10⁻⁶ for all conserved variables within 2000 iterations for this class of geometry, providing assurance that iterative convergence error is negligible relative to discretization uncertainty. Separate quantification of solver error would not materially change the credibility conclusion and is therefore not applicable for this assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error captures the risk that the model is applied outside its validated domain by an end user unfamiliar with its limitations. In this COU, the CFD model is operated exclusively by the originating FDA OSEL team under controlled internal procedures with a documented simulation protocol. The model output is not distributed to external users for independent regulatory decision-making; all predictions are reviewed by the assessment team before use. Consequently, the risk of uncontrolled use error is negligible and this factor does not apply to the current COU scope. If the model were to be disseminated as a shared computational tool, use error would need to be re-evaluated."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty encompasses epistemic uncertainty arising from the choice of governing equations and constitutive sub-models (e.g., turbulence closure, non-Newtonian rheology model). At MRL 2, the ASME V&V 40 credibility matrix does not require formal model form uncertainty quantification; the required credibility is achieved through output comparison against experimental data that implicitly bounds model form error. The Giersiepen hemolysis power-law model is the consensus approach in the field and its limitations are well-characterised in the published literature. A formal model form uncertainty analysis (e.g., multi-model ensemble) is not required at this risk level and is therefore scoped out of this assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty quantification addresses variability in material properties, geometric tolerances, and boundary condition parameters as independent sources of prediction uncertainty. For this COU, the model is used comparatively (RH relative to predicate device) rather than in absolute predictive mode; relative comparisons substantially cancel correlated input uncertainties. Additionally, the FDA GCBP geometry is a fixed reference geometry with certified dimensions, eliminating geometric input uncertainty. Fluid property uncertainty is bounded by the experimental characterisation of the glycerol-water analogue. At MRL 2, a full probabilistic input uncertainty propagation is not required, and the comparative use mode renders this factor not applicable as a standalone credibility concern."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The test samples factor assesses whether the physical specimens used in validation experiments are representative of the production device population, accounting for manufacturing variability across units. This factor is not applicable here because the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is a reference geometry fabricated under controlled conditions specifically for benchmark purposes; it is not a production device with manufacturing variability. All experimental data used for validation were collected on certified reference hardware. The concept of sample representativeness across a production population is therefore not meaningful in this context, and the factor does not apply."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses whether the input parameters used in the simulation match those of the physical test, particularly when the validation experiment and the COU involve different hardware configurations or operating fluids requiring scaling or extrapolation. In this assessment, the CFD model is validated against experiments conducted on the identical FDA GCBP geometry under the same CPB operating envelope with the same blood-analogue fluid. No scaling, extrapolation, or surrogate geometry is involved. Because simulation inputs and experimental conditions are directly matched without transformation, the equivalency factor adds no additional information beyond what is captured in the test conditions factor (assessed at level 2) and is therefore not applicable as a separate credibility consideration."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-osel-dbv",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels at MRL 2. Software quality assurance (L2/L2), numerical code verification (L2/L2), discretization error GCI <5% (L2/L2), test conditions matched within ±5% (L2/L2), output comparison within FDA round-robin uncertainty band at all 5 operating points with RH=0.87 <1.0 (L2/L2), QoI relevance directly traceable to ASTM F1841 (L2/L2), and validation activity relevance confirmed across three independent experimental datasets on the certified FDA GCBP geometry (L2/L2). Six factors (numerical solver error, use error, model form, model inputs, test samples, equivalency of input parameters) are documented as not-applicable with detailed rationale: each is inapplicable due to the controlled internal use context, comparative prediction mode, reference-geometry hardware, and MRL 2 credibility requirements that do not mandate independent assessment of these factors. No assessed factor falls below its required level; no offset rationale is needed. The credibility evidence collectively supports the claim that the CFD model reliably identifies worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for the Class II CPB device. The package is accepted.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
